shared_text:
Governor Phil Murphy
July 29 at 5:51 PM ¬∑

Great to join Superintendent Brian Brotschul and the Delran School District Restart Committee meeting today along with Tammy Murphy. This will not be a normal school year, but we‚Äôre committed to ensuring the concerns of students, families, and educators are heard and acted upon.

Above all, we must be guided by the principles of health and safety, high-quality education, and equity for all families. Our goal is to provide as much flexibility as possible for school districts like Delran to craft plans that fit their local needs.

post_text: The Delran Township Board of Education is accepting resumes and letters of interest for a board member to complete a one-year term. Must be a citizen of the United States of America, at least 18 years of age to qualify for office, able to read and write, a Delran Township resident for at least one year, not disqualified as a voter pursuant to N.J.S.A 19:4-1, not disqualified from membership for the conviction of crimes pursuant to N.J.S.A. 18A:12-1, a registered voter in the district. Information is to be delivered to Cande Kristoff, Board Secretary, Delran Board of Education Office, 52 Hartford Road, Delran, New Jersey 08075 by 12:00 p.m. Thursday, January 23, 2020.

post_text: How can you not love this town‚Ä¶
shared_text:
Delran Township Police Department
June 27, 2019 at 11:16 AM ¬∑

Delran school crossing guard receives a gift and letter from Delran Middle School Student.

On the last day of school, Delran School Crossing Guard Fred Pfeffer received a note and a generous gift from Delran Middle School Student Carrie Braga. Carrie said that Mr. Pfeffer has always said hello to her every day for the last three years that she has been going to the middle school.

Carrie handed Crossing Guard Pfeffer a note that read ‚ÄúThank you for always saying hi and brightening up my day‚Äú.

Fred Pfeffer, a retired Delran Police Officer has been a school crossing guard since 2005 and he brought the note and gift to our attention in hopes he could meet Carrie and her family to thank them.

Mr. Pfeffer and Carrie agreed to donate the gift to charity.

post_text: Are you in high school and have political aspirations?
shared_text:
Senator Troy Singleton
December 13, 2018 at 6:06 PM ¬∑

My office is currently accepting applications for prospective high school juniors and seniors (at least 16 years old) or college students seeking an internship from Jan-June 2019. Interns in my legislative office will participate in constituent service and local community outreach activities. They will also have the opportunity to actively engage in the legislative process by working on policy initiatives and, if schedules permit, they will shadow me for a day at the State House.

Strong writing and communications skills are necessary. Internships are not compensated, but qualify for college course credit at most institutions of higher education as well as community service hours for most area high schools.

If interested, please email your resume (college) or letter of interest (high school) to SenSingleton@njleg.org with "Internship" in the subject line by January 2, 2019. Or, please call Jennifer Aydjian at 856-234-2790 for more information.
